      "output": "         I Added Session Management to Aider | Lorbic     [](https://mastodon.social/@v1kash)                           [](https://lorbic.com/cdn-cgi/content?id=IGmduf8NRIGaR1BkA3fdjZoOAWIRPngnXnkqzbGpDnI-1783287734.689796-1.2.1.1-2qSkK82pbjasMNd7lZLshP_ZzLPg6LFis4xN0eFtqMU)[Skip to main content](#main-content)\n\n[\n\n# Lorbic\n\n](https://lorbic.com/)\n\n[Home](/)\n\n[Posts](/posts/)\n\n[TIL](/til/)\n\n[Reading List](/reading-list/)\n\n[Graveyard](/internet-graveyard/)\n\n[Newsletter](/nl/)\n\n[Studio ↗](https://studio.lorbic.com/)\n\n[\n\n# Lorbic\n\n](https://lorbic.com/)\n\n[Home](/) [Posts](/posts/) [TIL](/til/) [Reading List](/reading-list/) [Graveyard](/internet-graveyard/) [Newsletter](/nl/) [Studio ↗](https://studio.lorbic.com/)\n\nCommand Palette \n\nESC\n\nQuick Actions\n\nToggle Theme Go Home Posts TIL Series Explore Games Archive Reading List Tags Categories Newsletter About\n\nDate Jan 15, 2026\n\nReading Time 4 min\n\nSeries [Projects](/series/projects/)\n\nAsk AI\n\nConsult LLM\n\n[ChatGPT](https://chatgpt.com/?q=Read+this+technical+article+from+lorbic.com%3A+https%3A%2F%2Florbic.com%2Faider-session-management%2Findex.md.+Focus+on+the+implementation+details+and+provide+a+concise+summary+or+answer+my+specific+questions+about+it.) [Perplexity](https://www.perplexity.ai/search?q=Read+this+technical+article+from+lorbic.com%3A+https%3A%2F%2Florbic.com%2Faider-session-management%2Findex.md.+Focus+on+the+implementation+details+and+provide+a+concise+summary+or+answer+my+specific+questions+about+it.) [Gemini (Copy Prompt)](https://gemini.google.com/app) [Claude (Copy Prompt)](https://claude.ai/new)\n\n# I Added Session Management to Aider\n\nAider is my favorite AI coding assistant. It lives in the terminal, commits directly to Git, and actually understands my codebase. But it was missing one thing: the ability to save and restore chat sessions. So I built it. The PR never got merged, but I've been running my fork for months now. Here's the story.\n\n[open-source topic](/tags/open-source/ \"Open-Source\") [python topic](/tags/python/ \"Python\") [ai topic](/tags/ai/ \"Ai\")\n\nWORDS: 755 | CODE BLOCKS: 1 | EXT. LINKS: 3\n\nContents\n\n-   [The Problem: Context Evaporates](#the-problem-context-evaporates)\n-   [The `/session` Command](#the-session-command)\n-   [How It Works](#how-it-works)\n-   [The PR Situation](#the-pr-situation)\n-   [Why I’m Still Happy About It](#why-im-still-happy-about-it)\n-   [If You Want Session Management](#if-you-want-session-management)\n\nAuthor [![Vikash Patel](/images/170335550-140p.jpg)\n\nVikash Patel Senior Software Engineer\n\n](https://vikashpatel.net)\n\nLog Entry Type POSTS Record\n\n[](https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=I+Added+Session+Management+to+Aider&url=https%3A%2F%2Florbic.com%2Faider-session-management%2F \"Share on X\")[](https://www.linkedin.com/sharing/share-offsite/?url=https%3A%2F%2Florbic.com%2Faider-session-management%2F \"Share on LinkedIn\")[](https://api.whatsapp.com/send?text=I+Added+Session+Management+to+Aider+https%3A%2F%2Florbic.com%2Faider-session-management%2F \"Share on WhatsApp\")HASH COPIED\n\n \n\n[](/access-wsl-filesystem-from-windows-10-file-explorer/ \"Access Wsl Filesystem From Windows 10 File Explorer\")\n\n[](/setting-up-a-postgresql-container-a-quick-guide/ \"Setting Up a PostgreSQL Container: A Quick Guide\")\n\n[](/simplifying-search-activation-a-quick-guide-with-javascript/ \"Simplifying Search Activation: A Quick Guide with JavaScript\")\n\n[](/aws-host-static-website-with-s3--cloudfront--route53/ \"AWS - Host Static Website With S3 + Cloudfront + Route53  \")\n\n[](/setting-up-llama-2-with-docker-on-your-gaming-laptop-using-ollama/ \"Setting Up Llama 2 with Docker on Your Gaming Laptop Using Ollama\")\n\n[](/docker-custom-installation-location-windows/ \"How to Install Docker on Another Drive in Windows (D: Drive Guide)\")\n\n[](/build-nginx-from-source/ \"NGINX: Building from Source and Installation on Linux (Updated)\")\n\n[](/how-to-backup-and-restore-docker-volumes/ \"Docker Volume Backup: The 1-Line Command You Should Be Using (Instead of tar)\")\n\n[](/outline-vpn-over-https/ \"Stealth VPN with Outline over HTTPS\")\n\n[](/i-built-my-own-google-drive/ \"I Built My Own Google Drive\")\n\n[](/couchlens-couchbase-query-analysis-tool/ \"Introducing CouchLens: A Query Analysis Tool for Couchbase\")\n\n[](/dont-take-out-the-garbage-go-gc-deep-dive/ \"Go GC Deep Dive: How to Reduce Latency and Allocation Pressure in Production\")\n\n[](/clickhouse-as-a-vector-database/ \"ClickHouse as a Vector Database\")\n\n[](/aider-session-management/ \"I Added Session Management to Aider\")\n\n[](/building-production-ready-background-workers-in-python/ \"Building Production-Ready Background Workers in Python\")\n\n[](/cloudflare-management-with-terraform/ \"Migrating Cloudflare to Terraform\")\n\nReading part 14 of **[projects](/series/projects)**\n\nI’ve been using [aider](https://aider.chat) as my primary AI coding assistant for a while now. It’s the one tool that actually fits my workflow: terminal-based, Git-native, and it works directly on my local files. No copy-pasting into web forms. No context windows that forget everything. And not waiting for agents to keep thinking.\n\nBut it was missing one thing that drove me crazy.\n\n## The Problem: Context Evaporates[](#the-problem-context-evaporates)\n\nHere’s the scenario. I’m deep into a complex refactor. I’ve added 15 files to the chat, built up tons of context with the model, and we’re making real progress.\n\nThen one of these happens:\n\n-   I need to step away for a meeting\n-   I merge a big feature branch (need to change branches, aider detects repo changes and resets, loosing all context)\n-   My terminal session dies\n-   I accidentally hit `/clear`\n\nPoof. All that context is gone. The conversation history, the files I’d carefully curated, everything. Starting over every time was killing my momentum.\n\nI kept thinking: *tmux has sessions. Why doesn’t aider?*\n\nSo I built it.\n\n## The `/session` Command[](#the-session-command)\n\nI added a full session management system to aider. Five simple commands:\n\nbash\n\n```bash\n 1# Save your current session\n 2/session save my-feature-work\n 3\n 4# List all saved sessions\n 5/session list\n 6\n 7# Peek inside a session without loading it\n 8/session view my-feature-work\n 9\n10# Load a session (clears current chat and restores the saved one)\n11/session load my-feature-work\n12\n13# Delete a session you don't need anymore\n14/session delete my-feature-work\n```\n\nThat’s it. Now I can save context before stepping away, after hitting a good milestone, or just because I’m paranoid about losing progress.\n\n## How It Works[](#how-it-works)\n\nWhen you run `/session save`, here’s what happens:\n\n1.  A `.aider/sessions/` directory gets created in your repo root\n2.  The current state is captured: chat history, editable files, read-only files\n3.  Everything gets bundled into a JSON file with metadata (timestamp, aider version)\n\nLoading is the reverse, read the JSON, reset state, restore everything.\n\nThe sessions are project-specific (stored in each repo), so you don’t get cross-contamination between projects. And since it’s just JSON files, you can even version control them if you want.\n\nI put the implementation in `aider/commands.py` and added a full test suite in `tests/test_session.py`. The tests spin up a temporary Git repo and run all the subcommands.\n\n## The PR Situation[](#the-pr-situation)\n\nHere’s the honest part: **my PR never got merged into upstream aider**.\n\nI’m not entirely sure why. Maybe the maintainers are busy with other things, or maybe upstream is not in active development. These things happen in open source. Thanks to it being open source, I can still fork and build my own version to use it daily.\n\nBut here’s the thing: **I’ve been running my fork daily for months now**.\n\nCheck it out: [github.com/vk4s/aider](https://github.com/vk4s/aider)\n\nThe feature works great. I use it constantly. Every time I’m about to do something risky or need to step away, I hit `/session save`. It’s muscle memory now.\n\n## Why I’m Still Happy About It[](#why-im-still-happy-about-it)\n\nEven without the merge, this contribution taught me a lot:\n\n1.  **I got to dive deep into aider’s codebase** - Understanding how it manages state, handles commands, and integrates with Git was fascinating.\n    \n2.  **I scratched my own itch** - The best open source contributions come from actual pain points. This wasn’t a theoretical improvement; it was something I really needed.\n    \n3.  **I use it every day** - The feature exists. It works. I benefit from it. That’s a win.\n    \n4.  **Forking is fine** - There’s sometimes stigma around maintaining a fork, but if the upstream isn’t taking your changes and the feature is valuable to you, why not? Keep your fork in sync with upstream, apply your patches, and move on. I’m leaving my pr open in the upstream and when it’s merged I’ll use the upstream version. (:\n    \n\n## If You Want Session Management[](#if-you-want-session-management)\n\nIf you’re an aider user who wants this feature:\n\n1.  Clone my fork: `git clone https://github.com/vk4s/aider`\n2.  Install it: `pip install -e .`\n3.  Use `/session save|load|list|view|delete`\n\nOr just grab the relevant commits and cherry-pick them into your own setup.\n\n---\n\nContributing to open source isn’t always about getting merged. Sometimes it’s about solving your own problems, learning a codebase, and sharing the solution for others who might want it too.\n\nThe code is there. The feature works. And I’m still waiting for the day I can delete my fork because it landed upstream.\n\nUntil then, `/session save peace-of-mind` is my new best friend.\n\n---\n\nPS: I wrote this about 4 months ago, and a lot has changed, we have claude-code, antigravity. But aider is still my favorite AI coding assistant for working with monoliths.\n\n\\[ TOC \\]\n\nDOCUMENT INDEX\n\n-   [The Problem: Context Evaporates](#the-problem-context-evaporates)\n-   [The `/session` Command](#the-session-command)\n-   [How It Works](#how-it-works)\n-   [The PR Situation](#the-pr-situation)\n-   [Why I’m Still Happy About It](#why-im-still-happy-about-it)\n-   [If You Want Session Management](#if-you-want-session-management)\n\n[Previous Post Go Struct Field Alignment](/go-struct-field-alignment/) [Next Post ClickHouse as a Vector Database](/clickhouse-as-a-vector-database/)\n\nReading Series\n\n#### projects\n\n1.  [Access Wsl Filesystem From Windows 10 File Explorer](/access-wsl-filesystem-from-windows-10-file-explorer/)\n2.  [Setting Up a PostgreSQL Container: A Quick Guide](/setting-up-a-postgresql-container-a-quick-guide/)\n3.  [Simplifying Search Activation: A Quick Guide with JavaScript](/simplifying-search-activation-a-quick-guide-with-javascript/)\n4.  [AWS - Host Static Website With S3 + Cloudfront + Route53](/aws-host-static-website-with-s3--cloudfront--route53/)\n5.  [Setting Up Llama 2 with Docker on Your Gaming Laptop Using Ollama](/setting-up-llama-2-with-docker-on-your-gaming-laptop-using-ollama/)\n6.  [How to Install Docker on Another Drive in Windows (D: Drive Guide)](/docker-custom-installation-location-windows/)\n7.  [NGINX: Building from Source and Installation on Linux (Updated)](/build-nginx-from-source/)\n8.  [Docker Volume Backup: The 1-Line Command You Should Be Using (Instead of tar)](/how-to-backup-and-restore-docker-volumes/)\n9.  [Stealth VPN with Outline over HTTPS](/outline-vpn-over-https/)\n10.  [I Built My Own Google Drive](/i-built-my-own-google-drive/)\n11.  [Introducing CouchLens: A Query Analysis Tool for Couchbase](/couchlens-couchbase-query-analysis-tool/)\n12.  [Go GC Deep Dive: How to Reduce Latency and Allocation Pressure in Production](/dont-take-out-the-garbage-go-gc-deep-dive/)\n13.  [ClickHouse as a Vector Database](/clickhouse-as-a-vector-database/)\n14.  [I Added Session Management to Aider](/aider-session-management/)\n15.  [15 Building Production-Ready Background Workers in Python](/building-production-ready-background-workers-in-python/)\n16.  [16 Migrating Cloudflare to Terraform](/cloudflare-management-with-terraform/)\n\nShow all 16 parts\n\nShow Comments\n\n \n\nSYS.PERF LOAD: \\--ms | SIZE: \\--KB | REQ: \\-- | SCRL: 0%\n\nDispatch // Subscription\n\n### The Internet is Breaking.\n\nLet's figure out why. Get in-depth technical deep dives and architectural insights delivered straight to your inbox.\n\n \n\nJoin the Dispatch\n\nNo spam. Unsubscribe anytime. By subscribing, you agree to the [Privacy Policy](/about/privacy/).\n\nPowered by Lorbic Mailer\n\n### Welcome to the Fold.\n\nCheck your inbox to confirm your subscription.\n\n[Series](/series/) [Games](/explore/games/) [Explore](/explore/) [Archive](/archive/) [Tags](/tags/) [Categories](/categories/) [About](/about/)\n\n-   [](https://vikashpatel.net?utm-medium=lorbic.com)\n-   [](https://github.com/vk4s)\n-   [](https://mastodon.social/@v1kash)\n-   [](/index.xml)\n\n© 2017-2026 Vikash Patel. All rights reserved.  \nLicensed under [CC BY-SA 4.0](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/).\n\n[Privacy](/about/privacy) · [Terms](/about/privacy) · Built with [Hugo](https://gohugo.io) · [Theme](https://github.com/lorbic/hugo-theme-elarien) by [Vikash Patel](https://vikashpatel.net) · vcf1b521 · [llms.txt](/llms.txt) · [llms-full.txt](/llms-full.txt) · [markdown](https://lorbic.com/aider-session-management/index.md)\n\nThe views and opinions expressed on this website are solely those of the author and do not represent the official policy, position, or endorsement of any past, current, or future employer.",
